There are 365 students in the class, and there are 364 possible birthdays.

If we pick one person from the class, then the probability that they share a birthday with someone else is 364/365. If we pick two people from the class, then the probability that they share a birthday with each other is 363/365. The probability that they don't share a birthday is 362/365. So, the probability that they share a birthday is (363/365) * (362/365).
The probability of picking two people at random in this class who have the same birthday is 1/365.

Python is a high-level, general-purpose programming language. Its design philosophy emphasizes code readability, and its syntax allows programmers to express concepts in fewer lines of code than would be possible in languages such as C++ or Java. The language provides constructs intended to enable clear programs on both a small and large scale. It was created by Guido van Rossum in 1991. Python's design is computer-science oriented (unlike languages like Perl, Ruby, Scheme or JavaScript), with a bias toward cohesiveness and readability. It has a relatively "flat" learning curve, due to its full implementation of object-oriented features, implicit declaration of mutable data types, and automatic memory management.

Artificial intelligence (AI) is intelligence exhibited by machines. In computer science AI research is defined as the study of "intelligent agents": any device that perceives its environment and takes actions that maximize its chance of successfully achieving its goals. Colloquially, the term "artificial intelligence" is applied when a machine mimics "cognitive" functions that humans associate with other human minds, such as "learning" and "problem solving".

The Internet is a global system of interconnected computer networks that use the standard Internet protocol suite (TCP/IP) to serve billions of users worldwide. It is a network of networks that consists of private, public, academic, business, and government networks of local to global scope, linked by a broad array of electronic, wireless, and optical networking technologies. The Internet was developed in the late 1960s and early 1970s by the United States Department of Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (ARPA). The technology behind the Internet was first proposed by computer scientist Vint Cerf and other members of the ARPANET team in 1969, and the term "Internet" was coined in a paper written by Cerf's colleague Bob Kahn in 1974. Since its inception, the Internet has grown from a military research project into a global platform for commerce, entertainment, education, and social interaction.
